<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>INTRODUCTION</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BNI0026</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WRITTEN SUBMISSION FROM THE CHARITY BANK (REVISED)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Charity Bank (‘the Bank’)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">welcomes the opportunity to comment on the structure of the banking sector in Northern Ireland.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Bank operates throughout the UK and is authorised by the Prudential Regulation Authority and regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority and the Prudential Regulation Authority. Its mission is to finance charities, social enterprises and community organisations (CSOs). Since its launch in 2002 it has been a leading social finance provider, having approved over £180 million in loans to more than 1,000 CSOs. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Charity Bank has established itself as one of the leading social finance providers in Northern Ireland.  Operating from an office in Belfast, it has provided loan finance to organisations ranging from Omagh Community House to the Women’s Resource and Development Agency and raised £3.5 million in deposits over the past five years.  </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contains the Bank’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">views on the issues contained in the Committee’s call for evidence, especially question 4 concerning SME access to finance, which the Bank considers to be of key significance for the future performance of the Northern Irish economy. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ACCESS TO FINANCE IN NORTHERN IRELAND</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Committee seeks responses to questions concerning the functioning of the banking system and any repercussions for the growth of the wider economy and the flow of funds for start-ups and expansions. An analysis of market conditions in the banking sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is not straightforward because of the absence of relevant data. Earlier this year the British Bankers Association released an analysis of the geographical distribution of UK lending to small and medium</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sized enterprises (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SMEs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) (Geographical Spread of SME Borrowing, British Bankers Association, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">22</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> July 2013). Unfortunately, this exercise did not contain information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">identifying</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Northern Ireland. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Charity Bank notes the enquiry of the Competition Commission into the Supply of Personal Current Account Banking Services in Northern Ireland published on 15 May 2007. Although this did not address banking services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SME</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and was conducted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">before</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the ‘banking crash’ of 2008</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it did consider aspects relating to the general structure of the retail banking sector in Northern Ireland. Interestingly, it concluded insofar as personal banking was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concerned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “that Northern Ireland forms a separate geographic market…from Great Britain and the Republic of Ireland” (paragraph 3.37). The same enquiry also concluded that “by Q4 2006, the market was concentrated” (paragraph 4.23). Since the Office of Fair Trading (Review of barriers to entry, expansion and exit in retail banking, OFT, September 2010, paragraph 3.34) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">found that levels of market concentration for certain products had intensified between 2006 and 2010, it might reasonably be concluded that levels of market concentration in Northern Ireland have not relaxed and may have intensified since 2008. This is important because the level of concentration in a market is regarded as influencing the degree of competition existing within it, which in turn is frequently reflected in the availability and range of products and services and their price. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">A large portion of the organisations to which the Bank lends are unable to secure debt f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">inance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> from mainstream providers on terms that are both affordable and appropriate to the sector’s specific characteristics. For instance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> the practice followed by traditional lenders of seeking personal guarantees from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">charity trustees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> is not normally followed by Charity Bank. Trustees frequently act in a voluntary, un-remunerated capacity and it would be inappropriate for the development of social lending markets to impose this type of potential personal liability. Equally, if a borrower has been successful in raising funds on the back of the Bank’s support and is in a position to repay the loan early, it can do so without penalty. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">The financial position of CSOs in Northern Ireland will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">affected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> by the outlook for public spending. The Whitehall settlement to the Northern Ireland Office indicates an extended period of reductions in public spending over the period of the Comprehensive Spending Review. Experience suggests local authorities and other bodies responsible for public service delivery respond to public spending reductions by prioritising statutory services, with the result that activities which are non-statutory are disproportionately affected by funding reductions. Inevitably CSOs and especially bodies reliant on grant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">funding will not be immune. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">The data indicates CSOs in Northern Ireland play an important role in the economy. But there is evidence they tend to fragmentation and are reliant on grants distributed by public bodies for their funding. These factors contribute to a lack of scale amongst CSOs and as a consequence, can hinder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">their ability to fulfil the potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">to deliver services beyond the local and across a broad geographic area. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recent survey by the Department of Enterprise, Trade and Investment (DETI) (Survey of Northern Ireland’s Third Sector and its Potential to become more Enterprise Driven,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DETI, 2013) reported 77% of social enterprises had the intention to expand. But a number of barriers to expansion were cited, including “a lack of available finance”, “not having the right people” and “a lack of awareness of the support” available.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In assessing a loan application, the Bank reviews the salience of the organisation’s business model and business strategy and the effectiveness of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trustees and senior management in executing that strategy. The organisation needs to show </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is capable of securing sustainable revenue streams over an extended period of time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it can exercise control over its costs and generate free </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cash </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">flow. The Bank’s experience in Northern Ireland suggests a significant portion of CSOs are not sufficiently developed organisationally to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> loan finance with confidence. Internal data covering the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">twelve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> month period to the end of August this year </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">shows</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that very nearly a third of loan applications were declined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the Bank </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the grounds they failed adequately to demonstrate an ability to satisfy repayment criteria.      </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Bank believes solutions must be sought to aid the growth of the social economy in Northern Ireland. Charity Bank has experience of successfully managing and delivering a range of debt and development programmes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by way of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an alternative approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to reliance on mainstream banking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Examples include;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.67pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Building Financial Capability in the Aged Sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> - This programme, which is funded by Atlantic Philanthropies, has been operating in Northern Ireland since 2011.  The programme contains a strong element of aged-related sector support and encourages social organisations to consider their strategic financial sustainability options, including access to finance.  Working in partnership with Community Change, Sector Matters and University of Ulster the programme has been customised to provide a variety of interventions based on organisational needs.  Until the end of June 2013, the programme has supported over 180 CSOs in Northern Ireland to better understand their financial requirements.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.67pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">European Regional Development Fund (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">ERDF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">) Access to Finance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">rogramme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> programme operates in Yorkshire &amp; Humber and provides access to finance advice for CSOs together with delivery of finance workshops.  Since April 2012, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">ank has supported over 75 organisations in the region on a personalised basis.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.67pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">European Social Fund (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">ESF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">) Technical Assistance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">rogramme - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">This programme operates in the North</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">East of England providing access to finance and financial sustainability advice to CSOs.  Since its inception in March 2013, the Bank has been working with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">nine </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">organisations on a personalised basis and has delivered a series of financial workshops.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 30.67pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Third Sector Loan Fund </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">rogramme - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Funded by Yorkshire Forward (the previous Regional Development Agency), this programme ran from 2006 - 2011 in Yorkshire &amp; Humber. It combined investment readiness advice and a loan fund. It experienced growth in private sector investment from just over £200,000 in 2006 to £21 million by the end of 2011. Six hundred and five CSOs in the Region received investment readiness support and 251 organisations received loan support from the programme.   </span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regarding the question of specific service areas that might be appropriate for the development of CSO provision, those organisations that have a substantial asset base and good visibility of future revenue are particularly attractive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from a banking perspective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Social housing and social care are both services that fall within this category and therefore provide a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">basis for further expansion.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Charity Bank would like to take this opportunity to register its willingness to maintain a dialogue with the Committee as it further develops its views. In particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">if it was felt appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it would be delighted to amplify the evidence contained in this document. </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_Economic_data_that"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> October 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>